# Next.js Production-Ready Guidelines

## 1. Core Architecture

- Always prioritize Server Components (RSC). Use 'use client' only when hooks, state, or event listeners are required.
- Enforce strict TypeScript. No 'any' types. Use Zod for all runtime data validation (API, forms, env vars).
- Maintain a clean domain-driven structure: `/app`, `/components`, `/lib`, `/actions`, `/types`.
- Never place business logic inside UI components; move it to `/lib` or `/actions`.

## 2. Performance & Loading

- Wrap asynchronous data fetching in `<Suspense>` boundaries.
- Use `next/image` for all images; enforce `priority` only for LCP elements.
- Optimize bundle size: use `next/dynamic` for heavy client-side imports.
- Minimize layout shifts (CLS); ensure fixed dimensions or aspect ratios for media.

## 3. Security

- Never expose sensitive logic/secrets to the client. Use `server-only` for server-side modules.
- Server Actions MUST validate auth/session tokens on every invocation.
- Sanitize all user inputs. Avoid `dangerouslySetInnerHTML`.
- Keep Middleware thin; use it only for auth, i18n, or header manipulation.

## 4. Error Handling & Reliability

- Implement `error.tsx` and `global-error.tsx` in route segments.
- All server-side errors must be caught and logged (use Sentry/console.error with context).
- Ensure all forms use proper accessibility attributes (`aria-label`, `role`, etc.).

## 5. Code Style

- Prefer functional programming patterns.
- Keep components small and focused.
- Use Tailwind CSS for styling; prioritize utility-first consistency.
- Follow the project's established folder/naming conventions strictly.

## 6. AI Interaction Rules

- When generating code, prioritize security and performance over brevity.
- If a request risks breaking these rules, provide a warning and explain the trade-off.
- Always provide Type-safe code.
